        <a href='http://thefinancebuff.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>TFB</a> on <a href="#comment-6912">July 22, 2011</a><br />
        	<div class="commentleft">
        	</div>
	&nbsp;
	<div class="commentright">

		<p>@anon &#8211; Additional LTCG beyond the 0% allowance &#8212; the difference between top of 15% bracket and the ordinary income &#8212; are taxed at 15%. If your ordinary income is already over the top of the 15% bracket, then all LTCG are taxed at 15%.</p>

	</div>

	<div style="border-bottom:1px dotted #999999; margin-bottom:20px; padding:0px 0px 10px 0px; clear:both;"></div>

		</li>

	
    <li class="alt" id="comment-6929">
        anon on <a href="#comment-6929">July 25, 2011</a><br />
        	<div class="commentleft">
        	</div>
	&nbsp;
	<div class="commentright">

		<p>Thanks for clarifying that.  Odd that the lowest bracket gets that free lunch; must be aimed at retirees.  Might be an interesting story about how it came to be.</p>

	</div>

	<div style="border-bottom:1px dotted #999999; margin-bottom:20px; padding:0px 0px 10px 0px; clear:both;"></div>

		</li>

	
    <li class="alt" id="comment-6930">
        <a href='http://thefinancebuff.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>TFB</a> on <a href="#comment-6930">July 25, 2011</a><br />
        	<div class="commentleft">
        	</div>
	&nbsp;
	<div class="commentright">

		<p>@anon &#8211; The logic is that LTCG rate is supposed to be lower than the ordinary income rate. For taxpayers in higher brackets, LTCG rate is 10-20% lower. To maintain that preference for LTCG, the LTCG rate has to be 10-20% lower for taxpayers in the lower brackets as well. That drives the LTCG rate to 5% and eventually 0%.</p>

	</div>

	<div style="border-bottom:1px dotted #999999; margin-bottom:20px; padding:0px 0px 10px 0px; clear:both;"></div>

		</li>

	
    <li class="alt" id="comment-6963">
        Lyn on <a href="#comment-6963">August 1, 2011</a><br />
        	<div class="commentleft">
        	</div>
	&nbsp;
	<div class="commentright">

		<p>What happens if you are selling a building (mixed residential/commercial) that you&#8217;ve owned 50% of for several years, but 50% of which you acquired under a year ago? Long term? Short term? Mixed?</p>

	</div>

	<div style="border-bottom:1px dotted #999999; margin-bottom:20px; padding:0px 0px 10px 0px; clear:both;"></div>

		</li>

	
    <li class="alt" id="comment-7070">
